WRITING.TITLE: (The shining)(Doctor Sleep) Tony is actualy another human using his shine to help danny
WRITING.TEXT: I really doubt that this is something Kubrick intended in his version of the Shining. But after watching Doctor Sleep, i think that there is a case to be made about Tony actuly being another human who can also shine (at least in flannigan's perspective). In doctor sleep, we can see danny and Abra helping each other by talking inside each other's head and showing things to each other. Just like Tony in the first movie. On the other hand, there is a scene were Danny says to Abra that he used to think that he had an imaginary friend but it turns out it was just his shine, wich kinda pokes a hole in my theory. But a couple scenes later, Danny is desesperate and dosen't know what to do so he call for tony's help. Why would he try to talk with Tony if he knows he is not real? And why would Tony not answer? If tony is dany's shining then he should still be able to talk to him. I think the reason Danny cannot talk to Tony anymore is perhaps because Tony is dead (or maybe even captured by Rose? how cool would that be!). And one last thing, in the original movie, Tony always reffer to Wendy as Mrs Torrence. In the book, Tony is Danny from the future, i don't recall if he also says "mrs torrence" tho. Why would you call your own mother Mrs Torrence? Anyway, i'm not sure if this theory makes sense but i think i could have been a really cool idea to explore in doctor Sleep. Just imagine if Tony was one of the person captured by Rose the Hat and Dany ends up having to kill him!

In 2017, there was a 32% increase in the rate of homicides for Indigenous women victims (4.22 per 100,000 Indigenous women) from the previous year. In comparison, the homicide rate for Indigenous men (13.40 per 100,000 Indigenous men) increased by 2% in 2017. The homicide rate for Indigenous men has been increasing consistently since 2014. More than one-third (38%) of persons accused of homicide in 2017 were identified by police as Indigenous.Footnote9 This proportion has been increasing since 2014 when 31% of persons accused of homicide were Indigenous. The rate of Indigenous people accused of homicide in 2017 was 12 times higher than the rate of non-Indigenous accused (11.12 vs. 0.93 per 100,000 population). In 2017, the rate of Indigenous men accused of homicide (18.05 per 100,000 Indigenous men) was 11 times higher than the rate of non-Indigenous men (1.69 per 100,000 non-Indigenous men). This is the only time in my life i felt like something really weird happened and still have no explanation to it to this day. when i was a teen my bedroom was in the basement. The stairs to go down were right next to my room. One night i was not able to sleep and i heard sounds like someone was coming down the stairs. Like i would hear the steps crack one by one slowly going down but the sound was not loud enough to be my mom or my dad. Right before whatever was coming down the stairs made it to the bottom the sound stopped. I started feeling really weird and i could not stop watching my door frame expecting something to appear. I was used to hear weird things since my parents house is more than 100 years old so it always makes weird sounds. But this time it was different and i was truly scared. after like 30 minutes waiting for something to happen i finally tried to go back to sleep and just told myself that it was probably in my head. Then a couple minutes later i hear sound of somebody coming down the stairs but this time it is really loud and going down much quicker. I just saw a head appear in my door frame. I started screaming until i realised it was my mom... so i calmed down and she told me ''i'm sorry i scared you but i was wondering if you went upstairs earlier during the night because i heard somebody walking'' ... It was the only time my mom ever asked me something like this in the middle of the night so she must have really tought someone was there too.
